Date:  0/0/1840
Source:  Manners & Customs of the NZers
Author:  POLACK
Vol / Page:  1/1/5fn
Edition:
Quote:  Singular to relate, the central island has existed hitherto unnamed; as a distinguishing mark it has been called <i>Te Wai Poenenamu</i>[a-acute], or the Waters of Green Talc (<i>rather</i> an anomalous same for <i>terra firma</i>), from the time of Cook's survey; ... <i>Ibid.</i>1/194 ... a dark-gray and black-coloured granite, termed <i>onewoa</i> by the natives was made use of in its stead, or the green talc, <i>poeanamu</i>[a2-acute] and pieces of red jasper chipped off adroitly, resembling in shape our common gun-flints.
